def preprocess_student_data(df, pass_threshold=70):
    """
    Cleans and encodes student data.
    Adds Pass/Fail columns based on exam score.
    """
    df_clean = df.dropna().copy()

    # Map ordinal categories
    mapping = {
        'Family_Income': {'Low':1, 'Medium':2, 'High':3},
        'Parental_Education_Level': {'High School':1, 'College':2, 'Postgraduate':3},
        'Parental_Involvement': {'Low':1, 'Medium':2, 'High':3},
        'Access_to_Resources': {'Low':1, 'Medium':2, 'High':3},
        'Teacher_Quality': {'Low':1, 'Medium':2, 'High':3},
        'Motivation_Level': {'Low':1, 'Medium':2, 'High':3},
        'Distance_from_Home': {'Far':1, 'Moderate':2, 'Near':3},
        'Peer_Influence': {'Negative':1, 'Neutral':2, 'Positive':3}
    }
    for col, map_vals in mapping.items():
        df_clean[col] = df_clean[col].replace(map_vals)
    
    # One-hot encode binary categories
    binary_cols = ['School_Type', 'Extracurricular_Activities', 'Internet_Access',
                   'Learning_Disabilities', 'Gender']
    df_clean = pd.get_dummies(df_clean, columns=binary_cols, drop_first=True)
    
    # Add pass/fail columns
    df_clean['Pass_Fail_N'] = (df_clean['Exam_Score'] >= pass_threshold).astype(int)
    df_clean['Pass_Fail'] = df_clean['Exam_Score'].apply(lambda x: 'Pass' if x >= pass_threshold else 'Fail')
    
    return df_clean

# Load and preprocess data
df = pd.read_csv("StudentPerformanceFactors.csv")
df = preprocess_student_data(df)

Research Question 1: What is the best ML model to predict the final exam score? How can I improve the initial model?¶

In [9]:
def run_regression(df, model_type='linear', test_size=0.2, random_state=42):
    X = df.drop(columns=['Exam_Score', 'Pass_Fail', 'Pass_Fail_N'])
    y = df['Exam_Score']
    
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=random_state)
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)
    
    if model_type == 'random_forest':
        model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=random_state)
    else:
        model = LinearRegression()
    
    model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred, alpha=0.7)
    plt.plot([y_test.min(), y_test.max()], [y_test.min(), y_test.max()], 'r--')
    plt.xlabel("Actual Exam Score")
    plt.ylabel("Predicted Exam Score")
    plt.title(f"{model_type.title()} Regression: Actual vs Predicted")
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()
    
    print(f"{model_type.title()} Results -> MSE: {mse:.2f}, R²: {r2:.2f}")
    return model, mse, r2

linear_model, _, _ = run_regression(df, 'linear')
rf_model, _, _ = run_regression(df, 'random_forest')

Linear Results -> MSE: 4.15, R²: 0.73

Random_Forest Results -> MSE: 5.82, R²: 0.63

Roadblock & Learning: Decision Trees¶

Initially, I attempted to use a Decision Tree Classifier to predict exact exam scores. This was the wrong approach because classifiers are meant for categorical outcomes, not continuous values. As a result, the initial accuracy was very low (~21%), even after attempting to drop weak features.

This made me realize that Decision Trees are better suited for classification tasks. I created a Pass/Fail column using a threshold of 70 and retrained the classifier, which significantly improved predictive performance.

In [16]:
def classify_pass_fail(df, features=None, test_size=0.2, max_depth=4):
    if features is None:
        features = ['Hours_Studied', 'Attendance', 'Previous_Scores', 'Access_to_Resources']
    
    X = df[features]
    y = df['Pass_Fail']
    
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=42)
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=max_depth, random_state=42)
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
    plot_tree(clf, feature_names=features, class_names=['Fail','Pass'], filled=True, fontsize=10)
    plt.title(f"Pass/Fail Decision Tree (Accuracy={acc:.2f})")
    plt.show()
    
    print(f"Classification Accuracy: {acc:.2f}")
    return clf, acc

clf_model, clf_acc = classify_pass_fail(df)

Classification Accuracy: 0.85

The MSE is low because most students score between 60 and 75, making predictions easier, but R² is only around 50% due to many outliers.

def analyze_exam_scores(df, test_size=0.2):
    """
    Predicts exam scores using decision tree
    Returns: model, prediction error (MSE), and accuracy score (R²)
    """  
    # Remove unnessecary columns
    X = df.drop(columns=['Exam_Score', 'Pass_Fail', 'Pass_Fail_N'])
    y = df['Exam_Score']  # what we want to predict
    
    # Split Data
    # Divide into training (80%) and testing (20%) sets
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=42)
    
    #Train Model
    model = DecisionTreeRegressor(
        max_depth=4,          # Don't make tree too complex
        min_samples_leaf=5,  # Need at least 5 samples per leaf
        random_state=42    # Consistency
    )
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)  # Teach the model using training data
    
    # Evaluate
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)  # Make predictions on test data
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)  # How far off predictions are (lower = better)
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)   # % of score variation explained (0-1, higher=better)
    
    # Visualize Tree
    plt.figure(figsize=(34,12))#trialed and errored size to fit all squares
    plot_tree(model, feature_names=X.columns, filled=True, 
             max_depth=5, fontsize=10)
    plt.title(f"Exam Score Prediction (MSE={mse}, R²={r2})")
    plt.show()
    
    return model, mse, r2

# Run the analysis
reg_model, reg_mse, reg_r2 = analyze_exam_scores(df)
print(f"Regression MSE: {reg_mse}, R²: {reg_r2}")

Regression MSE: 7.712363312804017, R²: 0.5036873661329333

Research Question 1 Analysis¶

Linear and Random Forest Regression¶

  • Linear Regression outperforms Random Forest:
    • MSE: 4.15 vs 5.82
    • R²: 0.73 vs 0.63
  • Both models underestimate top-performing students (scores >80–85) due to majority of students scoring in 60–75%.
  • Models are reliable for predicting lower and mid-range scores but fail to capture features that make top scorers.

Implication: Regression models are useful for general performance trends but not for identifying highest achievers.

Pass/Fail Decision Tree¶

  • Accuracy: 85% — binary outcomes easier to predict than exact scores.
  • Top splits:
    • Hours_Studied
    • Attendance
  • Deeper branches: Social factors (e.g., Peer Influence) appear later.
  • Interpretation:
    • Students studying ≤27.5 hours and poor attendance (≤74.5) are highly likely to fail (low Gini scores = confident prediction).
    • Students studying >27.5 hours and with good attendance (>85.5) are likely to pass, especially with Previous_Scores >85.5 or Attendance >91.5.
  • Most influential factors: Hours_Studied, Attendance, Previous_Scores, Access_to_Resources.
  • Summary: Passing students tend to have high study time, consistent attendance, strong prior scores, and more support; failing students show the opposite.

Regression Tree Analysis¶

  • MSE: 7.712
  • R²: 0.50
  • Key splits:
    • Students with Hours_Studied ≤20.5: predicted scores lower (mean ~65.6), further reduced with Attendance ≤70.5 (~63) or Hours_Studied ≤15.5 (~62.9).
    • Hours_Studied >20.5: predicted scores improve (mean 67), further modulated by Attendance.
    • Top outcomes: Attendance >92.5 and Hours_Studied >24.5 → predicted mean ~73.4.
  • Conclusion: Hours_Studied and Attendance are the strongest determinants of exam scores; good attendance and study habits clearly link to higher achievement.

import statsmodels.api as sm # https://www.statology.org/statsmodels-linear-regression-p-value/
import pandas as pd

def plot_feature_score_relationships(df):
    """Visualizes relationships between social factors and exam scores using boxplots with data points."""
    
    # List of features we want to analyze against exam scores
    features = ['Teacher_Quality', 'Family_Income', 'Peer_Influence',
               'Parental_Involvement', 'Parental_Education_Level']
    
    # Create the main figure container
    plt.figure(figsize=(18, 10))
    
    # Create a 3x2 grid of subplots (for 5 features + 1 empty)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(15, 10))
    
    # Convert the 2D array of subplots into a flat 1D array for easy looping
    axes = axes.flatten()
    
    # Loop through each feature to create its visualization
    for i, feature in enumerate(features):
        # Create boxplot showing score distribution for each feature category
        sns.boxplot(x=feature, y='Exam_Score', data=df, ax=axes[i])
        
        # Overlay individual data points on the boxplot for better density visualization
        sns.stripplot(x=feature, y='Exam_Score', data=df, ax=axes[i],
                     color='black', alpha=0.5, jitter=True)
        
        # Add title showing which feature is being visualized
        axes[i].set_title(f'{feature} vs Exam Score')
        
        # Label the x-axis
        axes[i].set_xlabel(feature)
        
        # Label the y-axis
        axes[i].set_ylabel('Exam Score')
    
    
    # prevent overlap, neater
    plt.tight_layout()
    
    plt.show()
plot_feature_score_relationships(df)

def analyze_exam_score_impact(df, features=None, target='Exam_Score'):
    """
    Performs OLS regression to see how much each feature increases exam scores.
    Args:
        df: DataFrame 
        features: List of social features to analyze (default: Teacher_Quality', 'Family_Income', 'Peer_Influence', 'Parental_Involvement', 'Parental_Education_Level)
        target: Target variable ('Exam_Score')
    
    Returns:
        coefficients and p-values of features
    """
    # Set default features 
    if features is None:
        features = ['Teacher_Quality', 'Family_Income', 'Peer_Influence', 'Parental_Involvement', 'Parental_Education_Level']
    
    # Prepare data
    X = df[features]
    y = df[target]
    
    # Add intercept term
    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    
    # Fit OLS model
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    
    # Create results summary
    results = pd.DataFrame({
        'Feature': ['Intercept'] + features,
        'Coefficient': model.params,
        'P-value': model.pvalues,})
    
    
    print("OLS Regression Results")
    print(results[['Feature', 'Coefficient', 'P-value']])
    
    return model, results

analyze_exam_score_impact(df)

def predict_pass_fail_with_relationships(df, features=None, target='Pass_Fail',test_size=0.2, max_depth=4, min_samples_leaf=5, random_state=42):
    """
    Predicts pass/fail outcomes using only relationship-based features with a decision tree.
    
    Args:
        df: DataFrame containing student data
        features: List of relationship features to use 
        target: Target column name ('Pass_Fail')
        test_size: Proportion for test split ( 0.2)
        max_depth: Maximum tree depth (default: 4)#fits figure easily
        min_samples_leaf: Minimum samples per leaf (default: 5)
        random_state: Random seed (default: 42)
    
    Returns:
        clf: Trained classifier
        accuracy: Test accuracy score
    """
    # Set default relationship features 
    if features is None:
        features = ['Teacher_Quality', 'Family_Income', 
                   'Peer_Influence', 'Parental_Involvement']
    
    # Prepare data - using only the selected relationship features
    X = df[features]
    y = df[target]  #  we want to predict pass/fail
    
    # Split data into training (80%) and testing (20%) sets
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=random_state)
    
    # Initialize Decision Tree Classifier with optimized parameters
    # max_depth=4 was chosen because depth 3 and 5 had similar accuracy, 
    # but 4 gave the best balance
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(
        max_depth=max_depth,
        min_samples_leaf=min_samples_leaf,
        random_state=random_state  # Ensures consistent results across runs
    )
    
    # Train the model 
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Make predictions on our test section
    y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
    
    # Calculate accuracy -
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")  # Formatted to 2 decimal places
    
    # Visualize the decision tree 
    plt.figure(figsize=(27, 9))  # Large figure used trial and error to fit everything
    plot_tree(clf,
              feature_names=features,  # Use feature names
              class_names=['Fail', 'Pass'],  # Proper labels for our outcomes
              filled=True,  # Color coding by class
              fontsize=10)  # Readable font size
    plt.title(f"Pass/Fail Decision Tree (Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f})")
    plt.show()
    
    return clf, accuracy

#call funxxtion
model, acc = predict_pass_fail_with_relationships(df)

Accuracy: 0.75

Research Question 2 Analysis¶

Boxplot Analysis¶

  • Teacher Quality vs Exam Score: Median scores slightly increase from level 1 to 3, with similar spread and outliers. Teacher quality has minimal effect on exam scores.
  • Family Income vs Exam Score: Slight increase in median scores and high-score outliers as income rises, suggesting minimal impact on exam outcomes.
  • Peer Influence vs Exam Score: Median scores remain nearly identical across levels; spread and distribution are similar. Peer influence has little effect.
  • Parental Involvement vs Exam Score: Slight increase in median and spread from level 1 to 3, with more high-score outliers at level 3. Greater parental involvement may positively affect exam outcomes.

Regression Analysis¶

  • All factors are statistically significant (p < 0.05) with positive coefficients:

    • Teacher Quality: +0.48 per unit
    • Family Income: +0.48 per unit
    • Peer Influence: +0.49 per unit
    • Parental Involvement: +0.85 per unit

  • Parental involvement has the strongest effect on exam scores (almost double other factors).

  • Model has low explanatory power (R² ≈ 0.04) due to limited feature range (1–3) and low correlation. Small coefficients suggest moderate predictive value.

Implications: Schools could host annual workshops to guide parents on supportive, non-overbearing involvement in their children’s education.

Decision Tree Analysis¶

  • Accuracy: 75%, but all predictions are "Fail," indicating bias from class imbalance. High accuracy is misleading.
  • Gini impurity is low, showing good split quality.
  • Parental involvement is the most important factor, appearing as the first threshold in the tree.

def find_optimal_values(df, target='Exam_Score'):
    optimal_values = {}
    for col in df.columns:
        if col == target: continue
        if df[col].nunique() < 10:
            best_val = df.groupby(col)[target].mean().idxmax()
            avg_score = df.groupby(col)[target].mean().max()
        else:
            top_5pct = df[col].quantile(0.95)
            avg_score = df[df[col] >= top_5pct][target].mean()
            best_val = f">{top_5pct}"
        optimal_values[col] = (best_val, avg_score)
    
    for var, (val, score) in optimal_values.items():
        print(f"{var}: {val} (Avg score: {score:.2f})")
    
    return optimal_values

optimal_values = find_optimal_values(df)

Research Question 3 Conclusion¶

  • Key Findings:

    • Hours Studied >30 and Attendance >98% correlate with higher exam scores (70.9 and 70.8, respectively). Consistency and effort strongly influence performance.
    • Tutoring Sessions ≥ 6 show the strongest effect (71.7), highlighting the benefit of individualized support.
    • Categorical variables (Teacher Quality, Motivation, etc.) are optimized at level 3, as expected.

  • Surprising Findings:

    • Sleep Hours = 4 appears "optimal," contradicting typical health advice. Likely due to last-minute studying or specific student behavior (e.g., college students pulling all-nighters).
    • Physical Activity Level 6 correlates with better scores. Possibly reflects disciplined students with good time management.

  • Minor Factors:

    • Internet access, extracurriculars, student disability, and gender show minimal impact.
    • Public schools slightly underperform vs. private schools, explaining some preference for private education.

  • Recommendation:
    Students should prioritize tutoring, attendance, and study hours—these controllable factors have the most impact on exam performance, rather than factors like parental income or teacher quality.
